The *state pattern* is an object-oriented design pattern. The crux of the pattern is that we define a set of states a value can have internally. The states are represented by a set of *state objects*, and the value's behavior changes based on its state.

Let's implement a blog post workflow. The blog post starts as an empty draft. When the draft is done, a review of the post is requested. When the post is approved, it gets published. Only published blog posts return content to print.

Here's the intended API:

```rust
use blog::Post;

fn main() {
    let mut post = Post::new();

    post.add_text("I ate a salad for lunch today");
    assert_eq!("", post.content());

    post.request_review();
    assert_eq!("", post.content());

    post.approve();
    assert_eq!("I ate a salad for lunch today", post.content());
}
```

### Implementing the State Pattern

We define a `State` trait with the methods that all state objects share. Each state will implement the `State` trait:

```rust
trait State {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State>;
    fn approve(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State>;
    fn content<'a>(&self, _post: &'a Post) -> &'a str {
        ""
    }
}

struct Draft {}

impl State for Draft {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        Box::new(PendingReview {})
    }
    fn approve(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        self
    }
}

struct PendingReview {}

impl State for PendingReview {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        self
    }
    fn approve(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        Box::new(Published {})
    }
}

struct Published {}

impl State for Published {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        self
    }
    fn approve(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State> {
        self
    }
    fn content<'a>(&self, post: &'a Post) -> &'a str {
        &post.content
    }
}
```

### Encoding States and Behavior as Types

Rather than encapsulating the states and transitions completely so outside code has no knowledge of them, we can encode the states into different types. Rust's type system will then prevent attempts to use draft posts where only published posts are allowed:

```rust
pub struct Post {
    content: String,
}

pub struct DraftPost {
    content: String,
}

impl Post {
    pub fn new() -> DraftPost {
        DraftPost { content: String::new() }
    }
    pub fn content(&self) -> &str {
        &self.content
    }
}

impl DraftPost {
    pub fn add_text(&mut self, text: &str) {
        self.content.push_str(text);
    }
    pub fn request_review(self) -> PendingReviewPost {
        PendingReviewPost { content: self.content }
    }
}

pub struct PendingReviewPost {
    content: String,
}

impl PendingReviewPost {
    pub fn approve(self) -> Post {
        Post { content: self.content }
    }
}
```

This approach uses the type system to enforce the workflow: you can't call `content()` on a `DraftPost` because that method doesn't exist on that type. This is a more idiomatic Rust approach compared to the traditional OOP state pattern.

codeExamples.code:
trait State {
    fn request_review(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State>;
    fn approve(self: Box<Self>) -> Box<dyn State>;
    fn content<'a>(&self, _post: &'a Post) -> &'a str {
        ""
    }
}

impl DraftPost {
    pub fn request_review(self) -> PendingReviewPost {
        PendingReviewPost { content: self.content }
    }
}

impl PendingReviewPost {
    pub fn approve(self) -> Post {
        Post { content: self.content }
    }
}
